english:
  title: A Letter in Response to the Mongol Official
  author: Park Hwan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    As summer circles back around, I humbly consider that you, the Great Official of the Mongol Khanate—blessed by imperial grace and virtue—shall continue to flourish in ten thousand blessings. My humble realm depends entirely upon your protection and stewardship, and now we dare hope for the means to sustain our lives. Even the simplest folk feel the weight of your great kindness.

    In the year of Gichuk, when we sent our representatives to pay respects to the great Khanaate, it became custom that each year they would bring gifts as tokens of our bond. Yet unexpectedly, robbers arose and attacked them, bringing harm to your envoys. When your officials arrived, I hastily dispatched my elder brother, the Prince of Huian, to welcome them with provisions and words of comfort, and to explain the full circumstances. Your officials, satisfied, returned. We resolved that we would exert ourselves eternally in your service and sent emissaries repeatedly, humbly bearing gifts for your treasury.

    In the twelfth month of Musul, we dispatched Kim Bao-ding and Song Yan-qi to bring tribute. In the sixth month of Gihae, we again sent Lu Yan and Kim Kyom to offer our respects as before. When Kim Bao-ding returned bearing the Emperor's sacred edict, and again in the twelfth month of that year, we sent my younger brother, the Prince of Shin-an, bearing the customary tribute and additional gifts of local goods, with proper documents accompanying them.

    Just now, when Lu Yan and Kim Kyom returned with the imperial decree, they spoke of how you, the Great Official, graciously received my young brother and honored him with feasting for many days, sending escort envoys to accompany him to the imperial court. Upon hearing these words, my heart overflowed with gratitude beyond measure.

    Regarding your instruction that the people of the Yalu region should settle and cultivate the land, providing provisions and horses for passing officials—I dare not withhold my joy at your concern for my realm's welfare. Yet, as you yourself well know, our lands lie devastated and depleted. How could we hastily restore and resettle such ravaged places? Where circumstances permit, we have had even the humblest settle to welcome your emissaries, and for the most severely damaged regions, we specially dispatch officials to gather provisions of wine, fruit, and grain from elsewhere, bearing them here with diligent care. In time, as our people gradually recover, we shall faithfully follow all your directives.

    Regarding the reception of your envoys at my residence—I confess my dwelling is humble and unworthy, and shame overcomes me. Therefore, I have constructed a separate hall to receive your sacred edicts with proper reverence, and built a guest house to serve your officials with care. This is but a token of my respect in receiving you.

    As for the matter of Hong Bok-won's father residing within the old city, I have inquired of this man. He says: "My years are many and my illness runs deep; I cannot endure distant travel. Moreover, I have secured a position in the capital with good rank and ample stipend, and my means are sufficient. I have devoted myself to the practice of Buddhist virtue. How could I return to dwell in that fallen city?"

    This is most difficult, and his words are firm and resolute—his resolve cannot be easily swayed. Regarding all these matters above, I humbly beg that you, the Great Official, look upon our situation with compassion and extend your continued favor, so that my realm might forever exert itself in your service. This would be our deepest fortune.

    I send herewith humble local products of little worth, accompanying this letter. I humbly beseech you to receive them.
  footnotes:
    - The letter is addressed to a high-ranking Mongol official and concerns diplomatic relations between Goryeo and the Yuan Dynasty during the mid-13th century.
    - References to specific years (Gichuk, Musul, Gihae) follow the traditional East Asian zodiacal calendar system.
    - The 'Yalu region' (압록강) refers to the border area between Goryeo and Mongol territory.
    - This letter reflects the complex tributary relationship between Goryeo and the Mongol Yuan Dynasty, with careful diplomatic language expressing both gratitude and the realistic limitations of the Korean kingdom.
